Final Project: Understanding EU Immigration Dynamics: EDA and Predictive Modeling

1 Introduction: Supervised Learning Problem Description and Project Overview

The dataset analyzed contains information on immigration and emigration trends across selected European countries. It encompasses various demographic factors such as age, gender, and geographic origin of migrants, allowing for a detailed exploration of migration patterns over time.

Supervised Learning Problem Description:

Given the demographic and historical immigration data, the objective is to develop predictive models that can accurately forecast immigration in reporting reporting European countries based on demographic features such as age, gender, and country of origin.

Using supervised learning algorithms, models can be trained on existing labeled data where the target variable represents the total immigration to a particular European country within a specified time period. The models learn and identify patterns and relationships within the data to make predictions.

Overview of EDA Procedure:

  1. Data Preprocessing: This initial step involves importing the datasets and formatting them into suitable dataframe format for analysis.

  2. Data Cleaning: This step emphasizes the handling missing values, defining appropriate data types for each column, and ensuring the overall integrity of the dataset.

  3. Exploratory Data Analysis: EDA encompasses the examination of variable distributions. Insights into distribution of demographic factors and trends over time are explored and visualizations such as histograms, scatter plots, and time series plots will be utilized.

  4. Feature Engineering: New features are added and existing features are transformed to enhance the performance of models.

  5. Statistical Analysis: Statistical tests are performed to uncover relationships and dependencies between different variables.

  6. Dimensionality Reduction: Techniques such as Principal Component Analysis (PCA) are utilized to reduce the dimensionality of the dataset while preserving important information.

Overview of Analysis:

Various machine learning models used to predict immigration patterns based on the demographic and historical immigration data are explored. Models are selected taking into consideration factors such as interpretability, performance, and scalability. Then they are trained using preprocessed data, their performance is evaluated using metrics such as RMSE and MAE, and their hyperparameters are adjusted to optimize performance. Additionally, cross-validation is performed to assess model generalization performance and detect overfitting.

Overview of Results:

This includes performance metrics such as MSE, MAE, and other relevant evaluation metrics for both the training and test datasets. The results include visualizations of the performance of the models using appropriate plots and charts to provide insights into their effectiveness in predicting immigration patterns.

Overview of Conclusion:

Summary of findings including limitations, challenges, and potential future research.

2.1 EDA Procedure: Data Preprocessing

The following data preprocessing reads in datasets all found from Eurostat, the official statistical office of the European Union: https://ec.europa.eu/eurostat/web/migration-asylum/international-migration-citizenship/database

The initial datasets selected are:

  1. Immigration by age group, sex and citizenship
  2. Immigration by age group, sex and country of birth
  3. Immigration by age group, sex and country of previous residence
  4. Emigration by age group, sex and country of next usual residence

They contain data on immigrants/emigrants by age group, sex, destination country, and either the previous residence, country of birth, or citizenship of immigrants/emigrants.

The following additional datasets were loaded in during feature engineering and can be found from the Eurostat database as well via: https://ec.europa.eu/eurostat/databrowser/explore/all/t_popul?lang=en&subtheme=t_demo&display=list&sort=category

The additional datasets selected are:

  1. Population (National Level)
  2. Total Fertility Rate

# Create function to replace cells containing special values with NaN and addressing estimate and provisional special characters according to data keys
def replace_special_values(cell):
        if any(val in str(cell) for val in special_values):
            return float('nan')
        elif any(char in str(cell) for char in ['e', 'p', 'b', 's', '(', ')']):
            # Keep numeric values if 'e', 'p', 'b', or parentheses are present in the cell
            cell = ''.join(char for char in str(cell) if char.isnumeric() or char == '.' or char == '-')
            return cell.strip() 
        return cell

2.2 EDA Procedure: Data Cleaning

As population and fertility of the European countries were added later as part of feature engineering, data cleaning largely focuses on the immigration/emigration data.

After removing redundant data and defining a common dataset, it is apparent in the Eurostat data that some countries report immigration data by measuring the age of the immigrant at the time of immigration, while others report data by measuring the age of the immigrant that will be reached in the calendar year of immigration, and very few countries provide both measurements.

In order to minimize information loss, and given that if all data was complete then immigrants would be measured once by each method, the reporting European country age type with more information is used.

After selecting relevant data, mapping is applied to categorical variable types.

As the volume of missing fertility data is minimal, the information is entered from: https://wdi.worldbank.org/table/2.14.

While single the missing population entry is entered from the nearest available date from the UK Office of National Statistics found: https://www.ons.gov.uk/peoplepopulationandcommunity/populationandmigration/populationestimates/bulletins/populationestimatesforenglandandwales/mid2022.

The primary dataframe for analysis is df_immigration, with df_population and df_fertility data available as part of feature engineering.

data_frames = [df_residence, df_citizenship, df_birth, df_emigration, df_population, df_fertility]

def clean_data_frames(data_frames):
    # Extract unique years for each data frame
    unique_years_list = [set(df['Year'].unique()) for df in data_frames]

    # Find the intersection of unique years across all data frames
    common_years = set.intersection(*unique_years_list)

    # Intersection of unique 'geo_eu' values across all data frames
    common_geo_eu_values = ['CY', 'PL', 'DK', 'HU', 'EL', 'SK', 'UA', 'FR', 'LU', 'IT', 'LT', 'ME', 'FI', 'MK', 'CH', 'NL', 'CZ', 'PT', 'RO', 'SI', 'NO', 'ES', 'LI', 'AT', 'BE', 'EE', 'UK', 'IE', 'HR', 'IS', 'LV', 'BG', 'DE', 'MT', 'SE']

    # Values to exclude from dropping in 'geo_world'
    exclude_geo_world_values = ['RNC', 'UNK']

    cleaned_data_frames = []

    for df in data_frames:
        
        # Keep only rows with years that are common across all data frames
        df = df[df['Year'].isin(common_years)]

        # Keep only rows with 'geo_eu' values common across all data frames
        df = df[df['geo_eu'].isin(common_geo_eu_values)]

        # Delete 'geo_world' values more than two characters, excluding specified values if the column exists
        if 'geo_world' in df.columns:
            df = df[df['geo_world'].apply(lambda x: len(str(x)) <= 2 or x in exclude_geo_world_values)]
        
        # Remove rows where 'age' is 'TOTAL', 'Y15-64', 'Y_GE65', 'Y_GE85' if the 'age' column exists
        if 'age' in df.columns:
            df = df[~df['age'].isin(['TOTAL','Y_LT15','Y15-64', 'Y_GE65', 'Y_GE85', 'UNK'])]
        
        # Remove rows where 'sex' is 'TOTAL' if the 'sex' column exists
        if 'sex' in df.columns:
            df = df[df['sex'] != 'T']
        
        # Reset the index
        df = df.reset_index(drop=True)

        cleaned_data_frames.append(df)

    return cleaned_data_frames


# Apply the cleaning function
cleaned_data_frames = clean_data_frames(data_frames)

# Assign the cleaned data frames back to individual variables
df_residence, df_citizenship, df_birth, df_emigration, df_population, df_fertility = cleaned_data_frames

def separate_agedef_data_frames(data_frames):
    agedef_reach_data_frames = []
    agedef_complet_data_frames = []

    for df in data_frames:
        # Separate rows where 'agedef' is equal to 'REACH' and 'COMPLET'
        if 'agedef' in df.columns:
            df_reach = df[df['agedef'] == 'REACH'].drop(columns=['agedef']).reset_index(drop=True)
            df_complet = df[df['agedef'] == 'COMPLET'].drop(columns=['agedef']).reset_index(drop=True)
        else:
            df_reach = df.reset_index(drop=True)
            df_complet = df.reset_index(drop=True)

        agedef_reach_data_frames.append(df_reach)
        agedef_complet_data_frames.append(df_complet)

    return agedef_reach_data_frames, agedef_complet_data_frames

# Separate data frames based on 'agedef' values and drop the 'agedef' column
df_residence_reach, df_residence_complet = separate_agedef_data_frames([df_residence])
df_citizenship_reach, df_citizenship_complet = separate_agedef_data_frames([df_citizenship])
df_birth_reach, df_birth_complet = separate_agedef_data_frames([df_birth])
df_emigration_reach, df_emigration_complet = separate_agedef_data_frames([df_emigration])

def filter_and_clean(df_reach, df_complet, column_name):
    df_reach_filtered = pd.concat([df.loc[(df[column_name].notna()) & (df[column_name] > 0)] for df in df_reach])
    df_complet_filtered = pd.concat([df.loc[(df[column_name].notna()) & (df[column_name] > 0)] for df in df_complet])

    # Compare totals
    reach_totals = df_reach_filtered.groupby('geo_eu')[column_name].sum()
    complet_totals = df_complet_filtered.groupby('geo_eu')[column_name].sum()

    # Create cleaned data frame
    df_cleaned = pd.DataFrame(columns=['geo_world', 'sex', 'age', 'geo_eu', 'Year', column_name])

    # Populate column based on larger total
    for geo_eu in reach_totals.index:
        if reach_totals[geo_eu] > complet_totals[geo_eu]:
            df_temp = df_reach_filtered[df_reach_filtered['geo_eu'] == geo_eu]
        elif reach_totals[geo_eu] < complet_totals[geo_eu]:
            df_temp = df_complet_filtered[df_complet_filtered['geo_eu'] == geo_eu]
        else:
            continue  
        df_cleaned = pd.concat([df_cleaned, df_temp])
    
    df_cleaned.reset_index(drop=True, inplace=True)
    
    return df_cleaned

# Apply the function for each data set
df_residence_cleaned = filter_and_clean(df_residence_reach, df_residence_complet, 'world_to_eu_residence')
df_citizenship_cleaned = filter_and_clean(df_citizenship_reach, df_citizenship_complet, 'world_to_eu_citizenship')
df_birth_cleaned = filter_and_clean(df_birth_reach, df_birth_complet, 'world_to_eu_birth')
df_emigration_cleaned = filter_and_clean(df_emigration_reach, df_emigration_complet, 'eu_to_world_residence')

        df['geo_world'] = df['geo_world'].map(geo_world_mapping).where(df['geo_world'].isin(geo_world_mapping.keys()), df['geo_world'])
        df.drop(df[df['geo_world'] == 'TOTAL'].index, inplace=True)  # Corrected 'Total' to 'TOTAL'
    if 'age' in df.columns:
         df['age'] = df['age'].map(age_mapping).where(df['age'].isin(age_mapping.keys()), df['age'])

        df['sex'] = df['sex'].map(sex_mapping).where(df['sex'].isin(sex_mapping.keys()), df['sex'])

2.3 EDA Procedure: Exploratory Data Analysis

The exploratory data analysis begins with a correlation matrix and temporal plot of the initial four numeric data types:

  • (world_to_eu_residence): Immigration to Europe by the previous residence of immigrants.
  • (world_to_eu_citizenship): Immigration to Europe by the citizenship of immigrants.
  • (world_to_eu_citizenship): Immigration to Europe by the citizenship of immigrants.
  • (eu_to_world_residence): Emigration from Europe by the intended destination country of European emigrants.

The correlation matrix, 'Fig 1 Correlation Matrix of Immigration/Emigration, shows some anticipated correlations, such as the high correlation of birthplace and citizenship of immigrants, but also some less intuitive observations, such as the 0.60 correlation of immigration to European by previous residence and emigration from Europe to intended country of residence while the correlation of immigration to Europe by citizenship and residence has a correlation of 0.50.

The plot 'Fig 2 Temporal Trends in Migration shows there is some data loss in the varying immigrant measures, as the total immigrants annually should be the same regardless of geographic origin measures, however the behavior of total immigration to Europe from the year 2012 to 2021 is roughly clear. It is also evident from these Eurostat metrics that the emigration from these published European countries is significantly lower than the immigration.

Figures 3 and 4 illustrate how the single largest age cohort of immigrants is 25-29 and the distribution of immigrant age is centered around there and there tend to be more male immigrants from ages 0-59.

To compare immigrants to geo_eu, Figure 5 illustrates the total immigrants over the time period from 2012-2021 by selected European country and Figure 6 normalizes those values to the total population of the country in geo_eu (using data obtained from the additional data from feature engineering). One of the major observations of note are the countries with the most immigrants (Spain, Italy, the Netherlands) are no where near the most normalized number of immigrants (Luxembourg, Iceland, Liechtenstein).

While Figure 7 makes evident that the emigration data is not complete, it does show Spain reporting the highest emigration rates while the normalized emigration data in Figure 8 shows that Iceland, Liechtenstein, Lithuania, and Switzerland, some of which had some of the higher normalized immigration rates, have some of the highest emigration rates.

Figures 9, 10, and 11 aim to explore the data imported as part of feature selection.

2.4 EDA Procedure: Feature Engineering

In addition to the Feature Engineering techniques used in the previous section, additional unsupervised learning methods were explored to derive insights from the data. One such technique employed was K-Means clustering, which allowed us to identify underlying patterns and groupings within the dataset based on demographic and migration-related features.

Figures 12 and 13 introduce K-Means clustering. This particular clustering analysis focuses on the features added in feature engineering.

In [22]:
# Select the features for clustering
X = df_immigration[['geo_eu_fertility', 'geo_eu_population', 'citizenship_ratio']]

# Standardize the features
scaler = StandardScaler()
X_scaled = scaler.fit_transform(X)

# Determine the optimal number of clusters using the elbow method
inertia = []
for k in range(1, 11):
    kmeans = KMeans(n_clusters=k, random_state=42)
    kmeans.fit(X_scaled)
    inertia.append(kmeans.inertia_)

# Plot the inertia (within-cluster sum of squared distances) against the number of clusters
plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))
plt.plot(range(1, 11), inertia, marker='o')
plt.title('Fig 12 Elbow Method for Optimal Number of Clusters')
plt.xlabel('Number of Clusters')
plt.ylabel('Inertia')
plt.xticks(range(1, 11))
plt.grid(True)
plt.show()

2.5 EDA Procedure: Statistical Analysis

The statistical analysis begins with a continued look at the K-Means clustering visible in Figures 12 and 13. From the elbow method, the optimal number of clusters is 3-4.

The two-sample t-test compares the mean immigration rates between male and female immigrants. With a very low p-value (significantly less than 0.05), we reject the null hypothesis of ther being no difference in the mean immigration rates between the two groups. This suggests that there is a significant difference in immigration rates between male and female immigrants.

The ANOVA results indicate that the age variable is an important factor in immigration rates. The high sum of squares suggest that there is considerable variability not explained by age but the p-value of 0.0 suggest that there is significant difference in immigration rates based on age.

The chi-square statistic value is approximately 2,778,170, and the corresponding p-value is extremely small (approximately 0). This indicates a significant association between the year and selected European countries (geo_eu) in terms of the number of immigrants, suggesting that the distribution of immigrants across those countries varies significantly over the years.

2.6 Dimensionality Reduction

The explained variance ratio indicates the proportion of variance explained by each principal component. In this case, the first principal component explains approximately 65.47% of the variance, while the second principal component explains approximately 25.07% of the variance. Together, these two principal components explain around 90.54% of the total variance in the data.

From PCA, it is evident that the feature with the highest positive coefficient in PC1 is world_to_eu_birth, the feature with the second highest positive coefficient in PC1 is world_to_eu_citizenship, and the feature with the third highest positive coefficient in PC1 is world_to_eu_residence. While the feature with the highest positive coefficient in PC2 is eu_to_world_residence, the feature with the second highest negative coefficient in PC2 is world_to_eu_citizenshp and the feature with the lowest coefficient in PC2 is world_to_eu_birth.

3 Analysis (Model Building and Training)

This section predictive models are built and trained to forecast immigration patterns in the reporting European countries based on demographic and historical immigration data. The approach is one of supervised learning and utilizes Random Forest Regression and Linear Regression.

Model Types:

  • The Random Forest Regression Model constructs multiple decision trees during training and outputs the mean prediction of the individual trees for regression tasks. It was chosen for the ability to handle complex relationships and interactions between dataset features.

  • The Linear Regression Model assumes a linear relationship between the input feature variables and target variable. Although simple, it still provides valuable insight and can be used as a baseline performance metric for the more complex models.

Model Training and Evaluation:

The dataset is split into test and training datasets using a 20:80 ratio. For each model, a pipeline containing a preprocessing state and the regression algorithm. The preprocessing includes standardizing numerical features and encoding categorical variables.

Models are evaluated using the following metrics:

  • Mean Squared Error (MSE): Measures the average squared difference between the predicted and actual values. Lower MSE indicates better model performance.

  • Mean Absolute Error (MAE): Represents the average absolute difference between the predicted and actual values. Like MSE, lower MAE values indicate superior predictive accuracy.

Note: There are two sets of models built here. The first pair of models are the Random Forest and Linear Regression models that contain all the factors while the second pair of models do not contain any immigration information on birthplace or previous residence of immigrants.

In [31]:
# Define numeric and categorical columns
numeric_columns = ['world_to_eu_residence', 'world_to_eu_birth', 'eu_to_world_residence','citizenship_ratio', 'geo_eu_fertility', 'geo_eu_population']
categorical_columns = ['geo_eu', 'geo_world', 'age', 'sex']

# Define preprocessing steps
preprocessor = ColumnTransformer(
    transformers=[
        ('num', StandardScaler(), numeric_columns),  # Specify numeric columns and scaler
        ('cat', OneHotEncoder(), categorical_columns)  # Specify categorical columns and encoder
    ],
    remainder='passthrough'  # Keep any remaining columns as they are
)

# Define models
models = {
    'Random Forest': RandomForestRegressor(),
    'Linear Regression': LinearRegression()
}

# Split data into train and test sets
X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(df_immigration.drop('world_to_eu_citizenship', axis=1), df_immigration['world_to_eu_citizenship'], test_size=0.2, random_state=42)

# Train and evaluate models
results = {}
for name, model in models.items():
    # Create pipeline with preprocessing and model
    pipe = Pipeline(steps=[('preprocessor', preprocessor), ('model', model)])
    pipe.fit(X_train, y_train)  # Train model
    y_pred_train = pipe.predict(X_train)  # Predict on training set
    y_pred_test = pipe.predict(X_test)  # Predict on test set
    
    # Evaluate model
    mse_train = mean_squared_error(y_train, y_pred_train)
    mae_train = mean_absolute_error(y_train, y_pred_train)
    mse_test = mean_squared_error(y_test, y_pred_test)
    mae_test = mean_absolute_error(y_test, y_pred_test)
    
    # Store results
    results[name] = {
        'MSE Train': mse_train,
        'MAE Train': mae_train,
        'MSE Test': mse_test,
        'MAE Test': mae_test,
        'y_pred_test': y_pred_test  # Store predicted values for later use
    }

# Display results and plot actual vs. predicted values
for i, (name, metrics) in enumerate(results.items(), start=16):
    print(f"Model: {name}")
    print(f"MSE Train: {metrics['MSE Train']}")
    print(f"MAE Train: {metrics['MAE Train']}")
    print(f"MSE Test: {metrics['MSE Test']}")
    print(f"MAE Test: {metrics['MAE Test']}")

    # Plotting actual vs. predicted values
    plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))
    plt.scatter(y_test, metrics['y_pred_test'], label=f'Actual vs. Predicted ({name})', alpha=0.5)
    plt.plot([min(y_test), max(y_test)], [min(y_test), max(y_test)], color='red', linestyle='--', label='Perfect Prediction')
    plt.xlabel('Actual')
    plt.ylabel('Predicted')
    plt.title(f'Fig {i} Actual vs. Predicted Values ({name})')
    plt.legend()
    plt.show()

5 Conclusion

This analysis explored the performance of Random Forest and Linear Regression models in predicting world-to-select EU-countries immigration patterns. The investigation involved evaluating the models both with and without the inclusion of certain predictor variables, aiming to understand the impact of feature removal on model performance.

  • Summary of Findings

The results indicate that both Random Forest and Linear Regression models exhibited variations in performance when certain features were excluded from the analysis. The Random Forest model improved in performance while the Linear Regression model declined.

  • Impact of Feature Removal and Model Comparison

Upon removing select immigrant data, we observed notable changes in model performance, despite the high correlation between the target variable and said data. The Random Forest model demonstrated an improvement in both Mean Squared Error (MSE) and Mean Absolute Error (MAE) metrics. However, the Linear Regression model experienced a degradation in performance, with higher MSE and MAE values compared to the full feature set scenario. The Random Forest models were both competitive as target variable predictors while only the complete Linear Regression model appeared to be a remotely reasonable predictor.

  • Interpretation of Results

The contrasting behavior of the Random Forest and Linear Regression models highlights the differences in their ability to handle feature complexity and interactions. Random Forest's ensemble approach may have benefited from feature reduction by focusing on the most informative variables, while Linear Regression's linear relationship assumption may have been compromised by the absence of certain features.

  • Implications and Recommendations

The observed differences in model performance have significant implications for EU immigration prediction. Random Forest's ability to adapt to feature reduction suggests potential utility in scenarios where feature interpretability is less critical, prioritizing predictive accuracy instead. Conversely, Linear Regression's sensitivity to feature completeness highlights the importance of comprehensive data collection and feature engineering in EU immigration forecasting.

  • Limitations and Future Research

It is important to note that the dataset analyzed had aspects that were visibly incomplete. Future research could aim to acquire or estimate some of those aspects. Furthermore future research could look to evaluate impact of GDP, quality of life, or policy changes to advance understanding of EU immigration dynamics and enhance the efficacy of predictive modeling techniques.
